# Year range filtering — column selection on a DataFrame                                                          
   
The subject requires displaying only years 1800 to 2050, but the CSV likely 
contains years beyond that. This forces you to slice the columns by label 
range: df.loc[:, "1800":"2050"] or df.loc[:, 1800:2050] (after dtype
conversion). First time you slice columns by range rather than rows.

# Year range filtering — Row selection on a Pandas Dataframe

`iloc` stands for integer location. 
It selects data by position (0, 1, 2…), like indexing a list.
```python
s = pd.Series([10, 20, 30, 40, 50], index=["a", "b", "c", "d", "e"])
a    10
b    20
c    30
d    40
e    50

Single element:
```python
s.iloc[0]      # 10 (first)
s.iloc[-1]     # 50 (last)
```

Slice:
```python
s.iloc[1:3]    # b=20, c=30
```

Compare with loc which selects by label:
```python
s.loc["b"]     # 20 (by name)
s.iloc[1]      # 20 (by position)
```

The distinction matters when your index isn't 0, 1, 2… — like in your case 
where the index is years (1800, 1801…). iloc[0] always means "first row" 
regardless of what the label says, while loc[1800] means "the row labeled 1800."


Works the same way on DataFrames with two dimensions: df.iloc[row, col].

get_loc() returns the integer position of a column name in the index.
```python
# If your columns are:
# ["country", "1800", "1801", "1802", "1803", ...]

data.columns.get_loc("country")  # 0
data.columns.get_loc("1800")       # 1
data.columns.get_loc("1803")       # 4
```

It translates a label into a position number — like finding the index of an 
item in a list.

In your case it was used to build a slice by position, because you can't 
directly slice and pick individual columns at the same time in loc. 

So instead of:
```python
data.loc[:, yr_init:yr_end]  # works alone but can't add "country"
```
You get the positions and build the column list manually:
```python
start = data.columns.get_loc(yr_init)  # e.g. 51
end = data.columns.get_loc(yr_end)     # e.g. 101
cols = data.columns[start:end+1]       # slice by position
```

It's essentially doing for columns what iloc does for rows — converting a name to a number.

