Boolean filtering always returns a DataFrame because the result could be zero, 
one, or many rows — pandas doesn't know in advance, so it keeps the table 
structure.

loc() with a single label returns a Series because you're asking for exactly
one row. Pandas "flattens" it — the column names become the Series index:
```python

data.loc["Spain"]
# country      Spain
# 1800          29.5
# 1801          29.5
# dtype: object
```

If you want loc to return a DataFrame instead, pass a list:

```python
data.loc[["Spain"]]          # note the double brackets — returns DataFrame
data.loc[["Spain", "Italy"]] # also a DataFrame
```

The double brackets [[ ]] tell pandas "give me a subset of rows" (DataFrame), 
while single brackets [ ] say "give me this one row" (Series).

For plotting two series with plt.plot(), Series is simpler and gives you more 
control:
```python
spain = data.loc["Spain", 1:]
france = data.loc["France", 1:]

plt.plot(spain.index, spain.values, label="Spain")
plt.plot(france.index, france.values, label="France")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
```

Each Series already has the x-values (.index) and y-values (.values) built in. 

You control labels, colors, and styles per line easily.
DataFrame works too but it's more of a shortcut for quick exploration:
```python
data_plot = data.loc[["Spain", "France"], 1:].T
data_plot.plot()
plt.show()
```
The .T transposes it so countries become columns and years become rows — which 
is what matplotlib expects. It plots everything at once but you have less 
control over individual lines.

Bottom line: 
Use two Series when you want explicit control over how each line looks. 
Use a DataFrame with .plot() when you just want a quick look at the data.

#Visual separator for readability
It's just Python's way of writing 1000000 with visual separators for readability. The underscores act like commas in everyday notation — they're ignored by the interpreter and don't change the value at all.
```python
# These are all identical:
1000000
1_000_000
10_00_000  # any grouping works, though groups of 3 are conventional

# Works with floats too:
1_000_000.50
```
It was introduced in Python 3.6 (PEP 515) because large numbers like 10000000000 are hard to read at a glance, while 10_000_000_000 makes it immediately clear it's 10 billion.

